Dart&#39;s `Base64` encoding encodes *bytes* and a string&#39;s `codeUnits` are not bytes. They&#39;re UTF-16 code units. If the string contains only ASCII, or maybe even only iso-8859-1 characters (UTF-16 code units with values \&lt;= 255), then it&#39;ll probably do something reasonable. If not, the `Base64.encode` will probably just truncate every code unit to the lower 8 bits.

So you want to convert the string to bytes. The page you link to use UTF-8 encoding as default, so that&#39;s what I&#39;d do here too:
```dart
List&lt;int&gt; array = utf8.encode(invoiceHashValue_WithQRHash);
String invoiceEncodeData = base64.encode(array);
```

If you&#39;re going to do the same operation repeatedly, you can combine the codecs into one:
```dart
var base64Utf8 = utf8.fuse(base64); // First to last in encoding order.
// ...
String invoceEncodeData = base64Utf8.encode(invoiceHashValue_WithQRHash);
```

Doing this gives me the same result as the page you linked to for strings containing non-ASCII characters.

